TITLE: Using OSGi Service References in Java OSGi Components
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates the pattern of replacing *ServiceUtil with OSGi service references. By using @Reference, dependencies are injected via the framework, avoiding the potential for circular dependencies. The example includes the use of UserLocalService and Portal classes.
SOURCE: https://github.com/liferay/liferay-portal/blob/master/modules/util/source-formatter/documentation/osgi_components.markdown#2025-04-22_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: java
CODE:
```
import com.liferay.portal.service.UserLocalServiceUtil;

...

public User getUser(long userId) {
    return UserLocalServiceUtil.getUserById(userId);
}
```

LANGUAGE: java
CODE:
```
import com.liferay.portal.service.UserLocalService;

import org.osgi.service.component.annotations.Reference;

...

public User getUser(long userId) {
    return _userLocalService.getUserById(userId);
}

@Reference(unbind = "-")
protected void setUserLocalService(UserLocalService userLocalService) {
    _userLocalService = userLocalService;
}

private UserLocalService _userLocalService;
```

LANGUAGE: java
CODE:
```
import com.liferay.portal.kernel.util.PortalUtil;

...

public String getPathModule() {
    return PortalUtil.getPathModule();
}
```

LANGUAGE: java
CODE:
```
import com.liferay.portal.kernel.util.Portal;

import org.osgi.service.component.annotations.Reference;

...

public String getPathModule() {
    return _portal.getPathModule();
}

@Reference
private Portal _portal;
```

